metadata.name: Hyper-Vasarely #6
metadata.description:
This work is a tribute to Victor Vasarely. 

The algorithm reproduces part of the visual grammar of certain works by the artist and extends the resources used in his works by incorporating new elements. Each work is defined by the superposition of 2 or 3 layers made up of a grid of figures: squares, circles or triangles, each of which can be filled or hollow. 

Each layer has an evolution gradient that affects its color, and that can also affect other parameters of the figures in the grid, such as size, transparency, rotation or displacement. There are at least 8 different types of gradients that can affect each of these parameters.

At the same time, each layer can be affected by a subdivision into sectors that make changes to shapes, gradients, colors and the rest of the parameters. These subdivisions can be in the form of checkerboards, in either vertical or horizontal halves, or within an internal section.

The combination between the number of layers, their resolution (number of rows and columns of the grid), the subdivisions of the layers, the figures that are applied to each subdivision, and the gradients applied to the colors, sizes, rotations , transparencies and offset, generates a combinatorial explosion that is difficult to measure, but that undoubtedly generates thousands of different configurations within this visual grammar.


​​[s] to save a screen capture (5000 x 5000)

metadata.name: Finestre #96
metadata.description:
"Finestre" means windows or apertures in Italian. This generative art project was inspired by the appreciation of collected memories, windows in time to our past experiences and loved ones. Using basic geometry such as rectangles, squares, circles, ellipses, triangles with random compositions and many possible color palettes, Finestre presents our impression of portals to the Universes of collected memories through abstract still code-based outputs.

Finestre is a collaboration generative art project between generative artists Gonz0x and Schizzo.

Finestre has some fun interactive features which allows collectors to view the work in different configurations. For example, collectors can isolate the deconstructed background layers, isolate the main constructed layer, add Grain and also enter a Free Play mode which allows for the option to draw background and foreground layers, stacking infinitely. You can Save off a render as a .png.

Press "C" for Constructed Mode (Isolate Foreground)
Press "D" for Deconstructed Mode (Isolate Background)
Press "R" to reset to Default = C & D
Press "G" to add grain texture with each press
Press "S" saves render
 
Press "F" to toggle Free Play mode
In Free Play, Press "Q" repeatedly to add Deconstructed layers
In Free Play, Press "W" repeatedly to add Constructed layers

metadata.name: Formula on chalkboard 100% code #1
metadata.description:
Concept: 
¿Have you ever wondered what would your life be if you knew lots of math? Imagine you could calculate every single thing by just using your senses. You could potencially do everything.


Technical information: 
This is a full generative system of formulas on a chalkboard. Only uses a ttf for the typography. The name has an algorithm that combines syllables and vowels to make a unique name that can(almost) never repeat itself. Is doned using p5js and shaders. 

Interaction:
-click and hold left mouse button to paint on the board.
-click and hold right mouse button to erase the board.

Variations
-Color of the chalkboard.
-Displace of chalk.
-Primary graphic.
-Color of the drawing chalk.

metadata.name: Chaos Culture #623
metadata.description:
"Chaos Culture" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022.

《西遊記》第一回:「混沌未分天地亂，茫茫渺渺無人見。」

Chaos Culture is the final chapter of this series. There is a legend in the East that before Pan Gu opened up the sky and created the earth, the world was a chaotic place, and no one knew its appearance. And I have always been fascinated by this mythical story since he was a child.

These three works have a father-son relationship, Research > Memory > Culture, with each work re-growing through the remnants of the previous work, depending on its image. From the beginning of the creative coding, I like the concept of recursion the most. Here I experiment with my central thinking through this iterative relationship so that the work is not only the shadow of the artist but also the pulling force of repetition.

"混沌" Chaos in Eastern culture represents the initial state of things. This state is consistent with what we believe in generative art: Anything can happen if different forces are applied. Letting chaos grow out of order and then destroying it, the iterative process, is like my usual dialogue with myself, and maybe it's all just a diary.

Through these three series of works, whether I can eventually find everything in my childhood fantasy, I am not sure yet. The only thing I can be sure of is that I will continue to explore.

- Click the mouse to save an artwork.
- Collectors who own this NFT have the right to print the work.

Artist: Aluan Wang (ileivoivm).
Made with p5js and glsl.

metadata.name: NO ROADMAP #146
metadata.description:
This collection represents the need we have to move forward despite the obstacles that the road may present us.
We identify ourselves with the one who, even without the most optimal conditions, continues on its way until the goal is reached
Web 3.0 is a space that appears to us without a roadmap, so that everyone can explore it and learn.
Even though we only get to have a skateboard, in this journey of work and effort, we will continue asking ourselves until we can at last get it
WEN LAMBO?

+ 100 Roaders + Color variations
+ 50 Backgrounds + Color variations
+ 30 Foreground
+ 50 Animals
+ 25 Foreground elements
+ 10 Police cars on fire
